===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|warm|lang=enm}}, {{term|werm|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|wearm|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*warmaz}}, with different proposed origins:
# {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*gʷʰer-}} (warm, hot), related to Ancient Greek {{term|θερμός|tr=thermos|lang=grc|sc=polytonic}}, Latin {{term|formus|lang=la}}, Sanskrit {{term|घर्म|tr=gharma|lang=sa|sc=Deva}}.
# {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*wer-}} (to burn), related to Hittite (warnuzi) {{rfscript|und|sc=Xsux}} and to {{etyl|cu|-}} {{term|варити|tr=variti|lang=cu}}.
The dispute is due to differing opinions on how initial [[Proto-Indo-European]] *<tt>gʷʰ-</tt> evolved in Germanic: some think that *<tt>gʷʰ</tt> would have turned to *<tt>b</tt>, and that the root *<tt>gʷʰer-</tt> would instead have given rise to [[burn]] etc. Some have also proposed a merger of the two roots.

The term is cognate with West Frisian {{term|waarm|lang=fy}}, Dutch/German/Low German {{term|warm|lang=nl}}, Danish/Norwegian/Swedish {{term|varm|lang=en}} and Icelandic {{term|varmur|lang=en}}.

